N2  - Background: COVID-19 affected over 3 million people in Latin America, now considered the epicenter of this pandemic Reports from this region describing the impact of COVID-19 on the liver are scarce Thus, our aim was to estimate the proportion of hospitalized patients with COVID-19 and abnormal liver function tests (LFTs) on admission and evaluate its impact on mortality (NCT04358380) Methods: We conducted a multicenter prospective cohort study, including hospitalized patients with SARS-CoV-2 infection (RT-PCR assay) from 11 Latin American countries The study began on April 15th 2020 Exposure variables included clinical features, laboratory parameters, and specific/unspecific therapies for COVID-19. Abnormal LFTs were defined as ALT, total bilirubin (TB) and/or alkaline phosphatase (ALP) above upper limit of normal (ULN) on admission Primary outcome was death Multivariable logistic regression with odds ratios and 95% confidence intervals were calculated, calibration and discrimination assessed (ROC curves) Results: A total of 936 patients were included (57 1% males; age 50 7 ± 17 4 years); 27% had hypertension and 13% diabetes Most frequent clinical manifestations were fever (67%), cough (63%), dyspnea (40%) and sore throat (31%) Frequency of abnormal LFTs on admission was 41% (CI 38-44; n=386), including elevated ALT 34%, TB 5% and ALP 17% Among patients with elevated ALT, 10% had > 5 times ULN. Overall, 69 patients (7 4%) had chronic liver disease, 24 (2 6%) were cirrhotic, of which 10/24 presented acute on chronic liver failure (defined by EF-CLIF). According to imaging examination, 571 (61%) patients presented pneumonia, 299 (32%) developed acute respiratory distress syndrome, 145 (16%) required mechanical ventilation and 140 (15%) developed multi-organ failure Ninety-three (9 9%; CI 8-12) patients died with a median survival since hospitalization of 10 days (IQR 4-20). Mortality was significantly higher in cirrhotic compared to non-cirrhotic patients [25% (CI 9-46) vs 9% (CI 7-11); P=0 01; respectively] In the overall cohort, abnormal LFTs on admission were independently associated with death [OR 3 7 (CI 2 2-6 5); P<0 0001], adjusted for age, hypertension, diabetes, chronic kidney disease, body mass index >30, smoking and cirrhosis. (Table) Final model's discrimination was 0 81 (0 77-0 83) Conclusion: In this large multicenter registry from Latin America, a high proportion of patients presented abnormal LFTs on admission, which were significantly associated with death. Updated data will be presented at the meeting (Table Presented).
