N2  - Background/Case Studies: Volunteer (V) blood donors are uncommon in Peru, where blood supply is largely dependent on family/replacement (FR) donors. The objective of our study was to investigate the proportions of the two types of donations (V and FR) and to see if there is any difference in infection rates in donated blood from the two groups of donors at a hospital-based blood bank. Study Design/Methods: The blood bank records from 2014 to 2017 were used to determine the total number of V and FR donations. The results of enzyme immunoassays for detection of hepatitis B virus (HBV) surface antigen and antibodies to HBV core antigen, hepatitis C virus (HCV), HIV-1/2, human T-lymphotropic virus (HTLV)-1/2, Treponema pallidum, and Trypanosoma cruzi were reviewed in order to determine the proportions of positive results in blood collected from V and FR donors. Fisher's exact test was used to compare infectious disease rates in donated blood collected from V and FR donors. Results/Findings: There were 35,485 donations given during the 4-year period. FR and V donations comprised 98 and 2% of the donation pool, respectively. The proportions of each of the six infectious disease agents in the two donation types are presented in Table 1. There was an overall significantly higher rate of HBV (p = 0.0015) and T. pallidum (p = 0.0082) detected in FR donations compared to V donations. There was no statistically significant difference in infectious disease rates for HCV, HIV-1/2, HTLV-1/2, and T. cruzi between the two groups. Conclusions: The vast majority of blood donations came from FR donors. The overall detection rates of HBV, HIV-1/2, T. pallidum, and T. cruzi were higher in FR donations; however, the difference was only statistically significant for HBV and T. pallidum. Although the overall detection rates of HCV and HTLV-1/2 were higher in V donations, the difference was not statistically significant. Increasing the number of V donors may improve the safety of blood collected. Further investigation of the donor selection process may be helpful in identifying possible gaps that may explain the high seropositivity rates in collected blood.
