N2  - Background: The improvement in functional capacity after Cardiac Rehabilitation (CR) has prognostic implications and can be measured with a cardiopulmonary exercise test (CPX) The muscle efficiency (ME) at the peak of effort evaluates the peripheral capacity to transform the oxygen uptake (VO2) into mechanical work and has been proposed by our group to evaluate results after CR. Now we incorporate a new concept, the Muscle Efficiency Curve (MEC) and we propose it to evaluate results after CR Methods: We recruite 144 patients included in CR program (males 84%, age 53, in hospital program 68%) who underwent a treadmill ramp CPX pre and post-CR. We calculate ME pre RC at the ventilatory thresholds VT1 and VT2 and at peak of effort. We use this points to draw the MEC pre-CR. We also calculate ME post-RC at the same workload points used in the first test (VT1, VT2 and peak, on pre-CR test) and at peak of effort post-CR. With these points the CME post-CR is delimited (see picture) We compare the ME increments (pre-CR vs. post-CR) at each workload level and then analyze the results in 6 different groups: age (< 55 vs.>55), sex, body mass index (< 25 vs.>25), clinical risk (low, medium, high), CPX risk (based on SCORE+, previously described by us, see table: 0-1 low risk, 2-5 high risk) and CR program (in hospital vs home based program) Results: The MEC post-CR is located above the MEC pre-CR in all its points (increase of 6.13% at VT1, 5,48% at VT2 and 3.56% at the peak) When comparing both absolute peak ME, we obtain an increase of 12,69%. All differences are statistically significant. The patients with high CPX risk (SCORE+ 2-5) shows a significative lower improvement in ME. There is no difference between the other groups Conclusions: CR improves ME from early stages of the exercise resulting in a greater area under the curve comparing both, pre and post-CR MEC. A high CPX risk estimated with SCORE+ is associated with a lack of improvement. There are no difference between the other groups. Prospective studies are needed to assess the potential prognosis implications derived from these findings (Figure Presented) .
