N2  - Introduction: Few studies exist on suicidal behavior during pregnancy in our country, but it is known that mental disorders are important risk factors [1]. It is therefore essential to elaborate a profile of pregnants prone to this behavior so as to initiate suitable suicide prevention programs [2]. Objective: To study the incidence of suicidal behavior, and the profile and clinical features of pregnant women admitted to the emergency room for suicide attempts in a one-year period (2013). Method: Descriptive and prospective study by means of Clinical History according to DSM-IV RT diagnostic criteria and Pierce Scale for Suicidal Behavior. Results: Of 578 women admitted to our emergence room for suicidal behavior, 62 (10.7%) were pregnant. Age range was 18-44 years, with the two most prevalent ranges 18-25 y (28, 45.2%) and 26-33 y (22, 35.4%). As to civil status, the most prevalent were convivial union (25, 40.3%) and single (20, 32.2%). Suicide attempts were reported in 48 pregnants (77.4%), suicidal ideation in 13 patients (21.0%), and one patient completed suicide (1.6%). 50 patients (80.6%) reported a previous suicide attempt. Most prevalent clinical diagnosis was major depressive disorder in 45 patients (69.3%), at least 62.8% comorbid with borderline personality disorder; then, bipolar disorders (14, 22.6%), anxiety disorders (3, 4.8%) and schizophrenia (2, 3.2%). There were two principal motivations for suicidal behavior: conjugal conflicts in 51 cases (82.2%), and familial crisis in 8 (12.9%). Suicide was attempted within the first three months of pregnancy in 57 patients (91.9%). Principal methods were medication overdose in 41 patients (85.4%), and pesticides in 7 (14.6%). Eighteen pregnants (29.0%) opted for aborption. Conclusions: In this study, suicidal attempt was the most prevalent fact in pregnant, being mostly young, single or in convivial union, frequently repeaters, and the majority of suicide attempts occurred in first 3 months of pregnancy; conjugal despair was first stressor. Near 2/3 of patients fulfilled the criteria for major depressive disorder, generally comorbid with bipolar disorder. Most attempt were by taking an overdose, and 1/3 of patient had an abortion. There was one casualty [3]. The authors recommend that the risk of suicidal behavior be considered during the entire pregnancy period and postpartum, and that suicide prevention programs for future mothers be elaborated so as to prevent fatal consequences that are avoidable with early treatment [4].
