N2  - Objective: To evaluate the efficacy of platelet-rich plasma (PRP) combined with medical ozone (MO) in intra-articular injections for primary osteoarthritis of the knee (OAR), based on clinical and ultrasound evaluation of knees. Methods: 66 patients diagnosed with grade II-III OAR were selected for the study, 50 completed the study, who signed informed conset. Each received three applications MO (5cc) at concentrations of 20 ug / ml, and 2 cc of PRP in each knee with 1 week intervals. In PRP samples was determined before and after exposure to ozone by the Western Blot technique concentrations of platelet-derived growth factor (PDGF), and transforming growth factor beta (TGFb). Clinical evaluation of the knees was done by the WOMAC questionnaire before and at 6 and 12 months of treatment. The ultrasound of knees with transducer No 12, evaluated thickness articular cartilage, before and at 12 months of treatment. Statistical analysis: For the comparison of the average clinical scores on the WOMAC questionnaire and assessment of the average thickness articular cartilage Student's t-test was used for quantitative numerical variables. A P <0.05 was considered significant. Results: 50 patients completed the study: 37 were women and 13 men with an average age of 68 (51-89 years). The study showed significant clinical improvement within 6 months of treatment according to the overall WOMAC average, the improvement being smaller at 12 months (P's 0.0008 and 0.0124, respectively); assessment of cartilage thickness by ultrasound showed no significant changes after 12 months of treatment. These responses were not influenced by the demographic variables studied, except BMI. PDGF and FbTC the expression increased after ozone exposition. There were few adverse events which were mild and transient. Conclusions: The combination of MO with intraarticular PRP in patients with OAR is clinically effective at 6 months, lossing effectiveness at 12 months of treatment, showing no improvement of articular cartilage thickness at this time. Adverse effects are minimal.
