N2  - Background: Sexual assault and alcohol consumption are interrelated, bidirectional relationships between both behaviors have been described. Most of the research in this field has shown that perpetrators of sexual assault are known to the victim and are often close relatives, and that the victim's home is a common place of victimization. The aim of this study was to determine the prevalence and characteristics of sexual assault that occurs inside and outside the home in Peru and to measure the probability of being sexually assaulted by one's alcohol consumption pattern. Methods: A (2009) national cross-sectional survey was conducted among 57,313 Peruvian high school students aged 11 to 21 years with a selfadministered questionnaire that included demographics, alcohol and drugs consumption data and sexual assault data. A stratified two-stage sampling procedure was used to select students, and analyses were conducted taking into account the multistage cluster sampling. Results: Among females, prevalence of sexual assault inside and outside the home was 6.0% (95% CI: 5.6-6.5) and 6.4% (95%CI: 5.9-7.0), respectively; whereas, among males, prevalence was 5.1% (95%CI: 4.6- 5.6) inside and 6.1% (95%CI: 5.5-6.8) outside home. Among victims, inappropriate touching was the most frequent type of victimization inside the home in both female (20.2%) and male students (13.9%). Forcible kissing (16.9%) and “perpetrators showing their genitals to you” (12.7%) were most frequent in males in both settings. In a subset of respondents (45575/57313, 79%) who started to consume alcohol at least one year before the administration of the survey and that were past-year alcohol users, pastyear alcohol consumption was significantly associated with past-year sexual assault both inside (females: OR 2.7 [1.8-4.1]; males: OR 2.2 [1.6-1.3.2]) and outside the home (females: OR 3.0 [2.1-4.2]; males: OR 2.0 [1.4-2.9]). Females who got drunk and who consumed alcohol (but did not get drunk) were more likely to be sexually assaulted outside the home. On the other hand, only males were at risk to be victimized inside and outside the home when they drank to intoxication. Conclusions: Among Peruvian high-school students' sexual assault inside the home has similar magnitude as sexual assault outside the home, and varies by the victim's sex. Preventive campaigns should convey the message that sexual assault perpetrated by a person known or that occurring inside the home is a crime and hence, it should be reported to police.
