N2  - B-cell lymphoma, unclassifiable, with features intermediate between DLBCL and cHL, a provisional entity in the 2008 WHO classification, is defined by morphologic and immunophenotypic patterns overlapping between those typical for the 2 primary entities, after discounting their accepted variability. Owing to the complexity of overlapping patterns, the ambiguity in “accepted variability,”, and insufficient published data, these lymphomas are a diagnostic challenge, especially in cases that do not conform to the described patterns. Methods were review of H&E sections, immunohistochemistry, and relevant clinical and radiologic findings of 3 cases from routine practice. Patients were in the sixth to eighth decade; 2 of 3 patients were women; all 3 had generalized lymphadenopathy, and 1 each had involvement of liver and lung. Histopathologically, case 1 showed lymph node (LN) with nodular architecture, sclerosis, and a polymorphous infiltrate akin to cHL. Several nodules containing clusters of mononuclear and typical Reed-Sternberg (RS) cells were based in expanded germinal centers (unlike cHL). Distinct areas with confluent sheets of large cells akin to DLBCL in the same node. Case 2 showed morphology like cHL in LN and bone marrow replete with eosinophils and granulomas and of centroblastic DLBCL with admixed RS-like cells in concurrent lung nodules. Case 3 was morphologically like mediastinal DLBCL with delicate sclerosis and diffusely admixed RS-like cells in LN and liver. Immunohistochemically, neoplastic cells were positive for CD45 in 3 of 3; CD30 in 3 of 3; CD20 in 3 of 3; CD15 variable and focal in 3 of 3; PAX5, CD79a, Oct2, MUM1, BCL2, and BCL6 in 2 of 2; and EBER in 1 of 2. This study illustrates that morphologic and immunophenotypic overlap can occur not only as discrete regions within a single LN, but also in concurrently involved different sites. Furthermore, the morphologies may be sufficiently different in the 2 sites, raising the consideration of 2 different neoplasms, a potential problem when 2 different pathologists and /or 2 medical centers are involved in the diagnostic process. This awareness is critical to avoid misdiagnosis. Also, the clinical spectrum may be different from the presentation as mediastinal masses in young males as described for these lymphomas. Additional multicenter studies are needed to better define the pathologic features and to assess correlation of different patterns with biologic behavior.
