N2  - Purpose: To study the prevalence of Personality Disorders amongst persons who completed suicide and also in suicide attempters in Lima, Peru, between 2006 and 2010. Methods: Prospective and descriptive trial amongst people who committed suicide over the country, as well as in suicide attempters assisted at National institute of Mental Health Lima, Peru during the period 2006 to 2010, by means of psychological autopsy, police reports, medical information, references of Legal Medicine Institution, review of clinical histories, mass media and Internet information, relatives interviews, etc about former, and clinical assessment of patients in emergency room other in hospitalization area carried out by a multidiscipline team for latter, according DSM-IV criteria, including Personality disorders. Summary of results: Amongst 1715 subjects who completed suicide, it was detected 182 of them with criteria for at least one Personality disorder: 10.6%, being the most prevalent Antisocial Personality Disorder in 45% of them; in second place Paranoid Personality Disorder (jealous type) in 35% of them, and also the Borderline Personality Disorder in 19% of sample. Men were more affected by these disorders and there were reported not only suicide but also homicide in several cases. Regarding suicide attempters, amongst 3605 evaluated patients, 1784 of them suffered at least one personality disorder: 49.5%, being the most prevalent Borderline Personality Disorder in 72.6% of them; that is most frequently founded in female sex; then Antisocial Personality Disorder in 10%, after Paranoid Personality Disorder in 8.1%, then Dependent Personality Disorder in 5.8%, and Histrionic Personality Disorder in 3.5% of them. Less than 50% of persons who died by suicide as well those suicide attempters with personality disorders received adequate treatment. Conclusions: In this trial, 10% of people died by suicide suffered one personality disorder, being Antisocial Personality Disorder the most predominant personality disorder founded amongst people who completed suicide, while it is not so frequent in suicide attempters. Next disorder was Paranoid Personality Disorder, jealous type, also predominantely between men, better explained because of socio-cultural context, including homicide in several cases, although being much less frequent amongst suicide attempters. Just amongst these, it was found that, at least, half of them fulfilled criteria for a personality disorder, especially Borderline Personality Disorder, predominantly seen in women, following biological and psychological variables and comorbidity with depressive states and substance abuse or dependence, or Bulimia/Anorexia, as described in previous articles. No appropriate treatment, neither psychopharmacological nor psycho-social approach, for many of these cases was found. These findings are not quite different with those reported by other researchers, regarding methodology. So the authors recommend to explore the close correlation between nosological disorders with those of personality disorders for an overall comprehension of suicide behavior.
