N2  - Objective: To determine occurrence of completed suicide behavior in outpatients seen by suicide attempt in emergency and ambulatory services of National Institute of Mental Health across one year (2009) describing clinical and demographic facts, and formulate specific recommendations. Methods: Follow-up and descriptive trial in outpatients who attempted suicide, by means of telephone controls, home visits, survivors interviews, and revision of clinical histories adjusted to DSM-IV criteria, assessed by a mental health team, along one year. Statistical procedures were dispayed according SPSS-12.0 version. Results: They were evaluated 820 outpatients presenting suicide attempt across year 2009 (75% females and 25% males), and found 8 of them who completed suicide, this is to say above 1% from all, 6 females (75%) and 2 males (25%). Female age was between 24 and 51 years old, 4 of them unmarried and other 2 married; and male age was between 20 and 28 years old, both being single. Only one female reached university level, others high school studies. In 6 patients (75%) clinical diagnose were Major Depressive Disorder, while in one (12.5%) Paranoid Schizophrenic Disorder, and last one (12.5%) Delusional paranoid disorder. In 3 patients (37.5%) there were a co-morbid diagnose with Alcohol and Substance Abuse Disorder, in 2 female patients a co-morbid diagnose of Bulimia Nervosa, in other Sexual Identity Disorder, and in one male Borderline Personality Disorder. Five patients (62.5%) had been hospitalized by suicidal behavior in last five years. Two patients (25%) had a first-degree relative who committed suicide. Four patients (50%) died by self-poisoning, 3 of them (37.5%) by hanging, and one of them (12.5%) by jumping. Seven patients (87.5%) had been made more than one previous suicide attempt using several methods. Half of patients (50%) wrote a final note, including word text, e-mail message other mobile phone messages. At least 7 patients (87.5%) did not attend controls regularly and abandoned pharmacological and psychological treatment at all. Conclusion: In this study, female suicide attempter outpatients completed suicide more than males, by contrast to description for annual and also decade period scope seen in general population for this country [2], probably because assessed suicide attempters in the Institution were mostly females [1] and also by depressive and co-morbidity described states which involve mainly disturbance in serotonine system neurotransmission, furthermore there was a high degree of desertion of treatment not only by the poor adherence to prescription but for a weak familial or social support, so the authors point out the true relevance for enhancing followup procedures for this kind of patients, with implicit and explicit high risk for suicide, as the key strategy to prevent or reduce fatal occurrence.
