N2  - In 5 children at ages of 3 to l4 yr Brucellosis, caused by Brucella melitensis, was treated with Trimethoprim Sulfamethoxazol (Bactrim) in the form of syrup. The therapy lasted 3 mth. During the 1st mth the usual dose was given and reduced to half in the 2nd mth; during the 3rd mth the children received only 1/4 of the initial dose. Titer controls were regularly performed with the Widal agglutination test as well as by the slide agglutination test methods. All patients were clinically inconspicuous and generally well at the end of the observation period following the termination of treatment, and this lasted between 3 to 16 mth. The titers, at first significantly increased in all 5 patients, responded with variable intensity to the therapy and remained enhanced during the period of observation in 2 patients, possibly indicating a development toward the chronic stage of Brucellosis.
